<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="83944130ae65883552196d27d1f3ff66" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> How to sell your deck.<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.57)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10025'>Brad "Dr_Diablo" Peck</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=10025&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 12, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> I have played the Lord of the Rings TCG since the first day it came out in stores.  My brother, some of you may know him as Burger, and I are huge fans of Lord of the Rings, and huge fans of TCGs and CCGs having played Star Wars until they stopped printing more sets.  When I found out about this site, Decktech, it filled me with enthusiasm to read about other peoples decks and hoped it would make me a more knowledgable player.  In Star Wars, I found that there were countless numbers of deck types and strategies, some good, some not so good, but regardless, they were different.  You could see one player that had an Echo Ops deck for light side and a Hunt Down deck for dark win a tournament, and then come back next week with a Hidden Base/Endor Operations combination.  There was so much that could be done, and so much that was done.  Sure, it took a little more than a year and a half to completely change the deck building process, moving away from Mains and Toys, but it was done.  <br />
<br />
Then, we moved into Lord of the Rings.  It is still a relatively new TCG since the third set just came out, but I was surprised by how similar things seemed to be when looking at decks on Decktech and at the local tournaments.  I think I saw every person for a while starting Arwen and Legolas, and pulling Aragorn from their draw deck.  Looking at deck lists you would see 3 A Ranger&#39;s Versatilities in every deck, and eventually (especially right now) you would see multiple copies of Galadriel and her Mirror in almost every deck.  Now it&#39;s true, there are certain cards that are undeniably better than most others, but does this mean I can&#39;t win a tournament unless I make everyone else&#39;s deck and fill it with these godly cards?  I should hope not.  I love seeing a player drop down a Dwarf deck at a tournament, backed up by a conditionless Sauron army.  Now has this deck won.... probably not.  But that&#39;s not what&#39;s important.  I know the guy that played that deck, and he would show up every tournament with some slight variation of it, and would have a heck of a time playing.  Sure, he went 1-5, but that didn&#39;t matter.  He was playing a deck that he had made, and whether or not it could win, it was his deck, not some guy he copied it off.<br />
<br />
This brings me to my topic, and yes I know I tend to sidetrack a lot.  I&#39;m tired of reviewing decks on Decktech for the most part.  Countless decks have &quot;This deck is like all other Rangers/Moria swarm decks, just play it like that&quot; as their strategy section.  And people give them a 5 star rating.  It seems obvious that this player didn&#39;t make the deck, and may have very well cut and paste it from someone else&#39;s deck.  These are not the decks I want to see posted.  If you are going to take Clint Hays&#39; deck and change three cards, please don&#39;t post it, or if you do, make a link to Clint Hays&#39; deck and save yourself some typing.  It&#39;s no wonder all I can see at tournaments are (until recently) A Ranger&#39;s Versatily mixed with guided archery, while Galadriel mirrors away some minions, and Frodo exerts to use his Map to play the next site.  I&#39;ve stopped reviewing these decks, unless they have a strategy section that is longer than three sentances.  <br />
<br />
I read John Lolli&#39;s deck that won him the big tournament at Origins, which I unfortunatly didn&#39;t go to, and I gave the deck a 3 star rating.  Now you may be shocked, since it did after all win at Origins, but based purely on it being a deck in and of itself, it wasn&#39;t very good.  &quot;But if it isn&#39;t very good, then why did it win?&quot; you may find yourself thinking.  And yes, I&#39;ve thought that too.  But you must realize that John is very smart for playing an otherwise bad deck.  He played it simply to counter what he knew he would be facing.  Big Fellowships, Galadriel and Mirror, Shoulder to Shoulder and White Arrows were what he expected to play, so he put in counters for them, and they obviously worked well.  This is because every person at Origins, give or take about 5, was playing a similar deck.  Unfortunately, people were giving his deck ratings based on performance, and not on how the deck was built.  If he were to play in the finals against one of the few people that was playing a small Fellowship and Twilight Denial, I can almost assure you he would have lost, but because everyone figured large Fellowships with allies and Shoulder to Shoulder was the way to go, he probably had a much easier time.  No offense ofcourse John, but with a deck like that, playing the exact decks it was made to counter, you must have been pretty lucky.  You are still a great player though, to realize that winning would require a counter-deck.<br />
<br />
Anyways, I was off an another tangent again.  What I was trying to say was that because he won Origins&#39; big LOTR tourney, everyone thought he had a great deck, which is just not the case.  And they could tell that if they read the strategy section.  He said that he designed it to do exactly that, and if that&#39;s your meta, then you should do it too.  But, realistically, not every deck is going to play what he wanted to counter, and if everyone started playing choke decks the second day, he deck would be horrible.  But regardless, he gets one of the top decks on Decktech, with only writing a couple sentances for a strategy.  Another example of this type of thing is with Clint&#39;s day one winning deck.  I see only a bit of strategy written in the strategy section, which will only help people who know what the deck does already.  I am not saying your deck was bad, but I&#39;m just saying if you could write down for me what made it win, then I&#39;d be happier.<br />
<br />
Now, I don&#39;t mean to sound like I&#39;m trying to brag, but I feel that regardless of how well a deck could do at a tournament, if you don&#39;t write a good strategy section for others to see on Decktech, it probably isn&#39;t even worth me thinking about.  My strategy sections are always very long, and very thourough, and usually I will get four star rating that say my deck is pretty good, but my strategy is well written and therefore I deserve the four star rating.  Now I&#39;ve never won a tournament, and I&#39;ve actually never even been close.  I think most of it comes from unlucky draws, but regardless of my position at the end of the tournament, my deck was one that I created with no help and that I&#39;m happy about.  If you want to review my decks, you will see that they probably aren&#39;t the best decks around, and usually don&#39;t get the job done, but they are explained to the best of my ability and therefore deserve a bit of credit.  How am I supposed to know whether or not some of the posters on Decktech have actually created their own deck?  Most of the time, if they explain it well, I can infer that it is their own creation since they told me the reason each card was in there.  And for the decks that explain nothing, then it&#39;s fairly obvious that they have read other decks and used those people&#39;s strategies.  Again, I don&#39;t mean to offend anyone, but writing a strategy section that is thourough makes you seem like a more knowledgable player, and helps out other players that are reviewing your deck.<br />
<br />
I&#39;ll say this in closing, and hopefully some of you are still reading this.  When you post your deck, write your strategy as though some kid who has never played a game, and had just bought his first starter deck is reading this.  Think of your strategy section as a way of inviting people into the game, and telling them that your deck type is not one to mess with.  If they read your strategy and feel lost or confused about why certain things are in there, obviously you didn&#39;t do your job well.  When I post a deck, I write it as though a newbie is reading it, so that I can help them learn about what different cards do, and which ones work better in decks.  Without a strategy section, your deck means very little to me, and you can expect a rating lower than I would give if you explained everything.  <br />
<br />
Oh, and as a final note, if I do review your deck with a three or four star rating, and tell you to write a better strategy section next time, please do not send me threats over D-mail, I say it for your own good.  As well, though this is somewhat a rant, I think it is a little helpful for other, so please if you wish to judge it as a rant, send me a D-mail and don&#39;t review it.<br />
<br />
Thanks for your time,   Brad. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=3864&view=1&PHPSESSID=83944130ae65883552196d27d1f3ff66'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=83944130ae65883552196d27d1f3ff66'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=83944130ae65883552196d27d1f3ff66'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
